					<description><![CDATA[<p>NewOrbit has raised $18.5 million in Series A financing to pioneer the commercialisation of Very Low Earth Orbit (VLEO). This is a vote of confidence in the UK satellite manufacturer</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/neworbit-raises-18-5m-to-expand-vleo-satellite-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">NewOrbit Raises $18.5M to Expand VLEO Satellite Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://ventureburn.com/galvany-raises-e10m-to-accelerate-energy-transition/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">NewOrbit </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has raised $18.5 million in Series A </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/galvany-raises-e10m-to-accelerate-energy-transition/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">financing </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">to pioneer the commercialisation of Very Low Earth Orbit (VLEO). This is a vote of confidence in the UK satellite manufacturer as it prepares to launch the world&#8217;s first commercial satellite in the ultra-low 200–300 km atmospheric layer.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Voyager Ventures, an early-stage deep tech/decarbonisation fund, led the round. The round also saw participation from tech giants, such as David Kirk (former chief scientist at NVIDIA), Lawrence Leuschner (co-founder and former CEO of TIER Mobility), and the family office Custos. Previous seed backers, including Atlantic.VC, Lifeline Ventures, LGF, and Illusian doubled down on their support, pushing NewOrbit’s total capitalisation to $27.8 million.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Conquering the 60-Year Orbital Blindspot</span></h2>
<div>
<div data-test-render-count="1">
<div class="group">
<div class="contents">
<div class="group relative relative pb-3" data-is-streaming="false">
<div class="font-claude-response relative leading-[1.65rem] [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:bg-bg-000/50 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8">
<div>
<div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown">
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">For over six decades, the global space industry has treated VLEO as a hostile &#8220;no man&#8217;s land&#8221;, occupied only by the ISS and short-lived military spy satellites. Conventional commercial satellites reside much higher up, typically in standard Low Earth Orbit (LEO) at altitudes above 500 km.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Three severe physics obstacles have historically rendered VLEO commercially unviable:</span></p>
<ol>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Aerodynamic Drag:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Residual atmospheric particles at 200 km quickly slow down travelling hardware, causing spacecraft to lose altitude and burn up in the atmosphere within a matter of weeks.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Atomic Oxygen Corrosion:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> The oxygen at this altitude is in an extremely reactive state as a single atom. The atmosphere is so corrosive that the solar cell, thermal coating and optical sensors can be quickly destroyed by it.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Aerodynamic Torques:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Pockets of atmospheric resistance exert physical twisting forces on the satellite bus, continually knocking sensors and communication dishes out of alignment.</span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">NewOrbit claims to have overcome these environmental hurdles with its purpose-engineered NEO-1 satellite bus. Propelled by a proprietary, air-breathing ion propulsion engine, the spacecraft is designed to perform continuous, micro-thruster counter-boosts to neutralise atmospheric drag. Paired with highly resilient, custom material coatings, NewOrbit projects its hardware will achieve an operational lifespan of up to five years in deep VLEO conditions.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202563" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202563" class="size-large wp-image-202563" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Satellite-picture-1024x683.jpg" alt="Satellite picture" width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-202563" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;For sixty years, VLEO has been avoided because it was deemed too aggressive an environment for commercial spacecraft,&#8221; said Anatolii Papulov, CEO and co-founder of NewOrbit. &#8220;But in reality, it is the most valuable empty real estate in space. We built NEO-1 to tame this environment, opening a completely new layer of critical infrastructure.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/galvany-raises-e10m-to-accelerate-energy-transition/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">GALVANY Raises €10M to Accelerate Energy Transition</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Commercial Logic: Drone Resolution at a Fraction of the Cost</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The strategic rationale driving Voyager Ventures’ investment centres on simple orbital geometry: the closer a satellite is to the ground, the less physical effort it takes to capture high-definition imagery or transmit data.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">NewOrbit estimates that operating from a 200 km perch will allow its payload sensors to deliver drone-quality, sub-metre Earth observation imagery at roughly 20 times less cost than traditional LEO satellite constellations. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Additionally, the extreme proximity drastically reduces data propagation delays, paving the way for low-latency space applications like seamless 5G direct-to-device mobile connectivity and uninterrupted, live HD video streaming without the need for high-gain external amplifiers or specialised consumer antennas.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;VLEO represents the next foundational paradigm shift in the global space sector,&#8221; noted Matthew Blain, partner at Voyager Ventures. &#8220;The technology unlocks order-of-magnitude performance improvements in Earth data at a fraction of today&#8217;s capital expenditure. NewOrbit has the engineering discipline to lead this global category right from the UK.&#8221;</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Building Europe&#8217;s Largest VLEO Manufacturing Base</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The $18.5 million influx of Series A capital is strictly meant for scaling NewOrbit’s physical infrastructure. The primary project is the development of the NEO Production Complex in the UK Thames Valley, scheduled to be operational in 2027.</span></p>
<p>The company will use the advanced facility for final assembly, integration, and testing of the NEO-1 satellite before its 2028 debut. The facility will initially produce 10 satellites per year. At full capacity, the complex will become Europe&#8217;s largest dedicated VLEO manufacturing plant, serving Europe&#8217;s sovereign space ecosystem.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To execute this rapid scaling roadmap, NewOrbit has assembled an elite multidisciplinary team, recruiting specialised talent directly from SpaceX, NASA’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL), Tesla, Airbus, and Formula 1. The startup’s advisory board is equally formidable. featuring Jean-Jacques Dordain, the former Director General of the European Space Agency (ESA), and Sir Chris Deverell, the former Commander of the UK Joint Forces.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/neworbit-raises-18-5m-to-expand-vleo-satellite-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">NewOrbit Raises $18.5M to Expand VLEO Satellite Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
